    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Bernoulli's principle is a bit like a magical trick that the airfoil performs. When air flows over the curved top surface of the wing, it has to travel faster than the air below, which is flatter. This speed difference creates a pressure difference, with lower pressure above the wing and higher pressure below. It's like a secret passageway for the air, which makes the wing want to go up, hence lift! Think of it as a clever game of hide and seek, where the fast-moving air is the sneaky one hiding from the slower air, creating an invisible force that lifts the wing up.",
