    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure, let's delve into the math a bit. According to Bernoulli's principle, for an incompressible flow, the sum of the pressure energy, kinetic energy, and potential energy per unit volume is constant along a streamline. Mathematically, this is expressed as P + ½ρv² + ρgh = constant, where P is pressure, ρ is density, v is velocity, and h is height. In the case of an airfoil, the height (h) doesn't change significantly, so the pressure (P) and velocity (v) are inversely related. As the air moves faster over the curved upper surface of the wing, its velocity (v) increases, and therefore, the pressure (P) must decrease to keep the sum constant.\n\nNow, about the air sticking to the curve, this is due to the Coanda effect. When the air flows over the curved surface of the wing, it tends to follow the path of least resistance, which is the curved surface. This is a result of the air's viscosity and the boundary layer that forms along the wing's surface. The air molecules stick to the wing's surface because of friction, and as they slow down due to the curvature, they",
      "source": "target",
